Linear Model for Forecasting the Total Number of Newly Established Firms

Tufan Berk Tug - IE360 - Fall 2020

1.Introduction

In this study, the aim is to create a linear model to yield sensible forecasts on the number of newly established firms, using related independent data from EVDS. Since the number of newly established firms highly depends on the general economic situation, most of the considered data is indicators of the general economic situation of Turkey. Lets check which variables are considered for what reason: Total Industrial Production: Since most of the companies use the goods produced by industries in Turkey as raw material, volume of this production may be highly correlated with the new enterprises. High production volumes would create surplus, which can be a good incentive to start new businesses. Exchange Rates and Interest Rates: Exchange rates are one of the most valuable data in the domain of economic research. Any fluctuation in the exchange rates affects all businesses as we have an open market economy conditions in Turkey. On the other hand, interest rates are also very important since it determines the attractiveness of using loans to start businesses. It should be noted that commercial loans average interest rates are used since it is the one used for businesses. Producer Price Index: Just like the volume of industrial production, prices of the goods used by producers are very important factors. In times that it is relatively cheaper to run a business due to low PPI, people will be more encouraged to start new enterprises. Financial Situation of Household and General Economic Situation: Because it is very risky to start a business from scratch, it is likely that the financial situation of people is correlated with our target variable. Also the perceived general economic situation of the country is also important since customers of businesses are residents of the country most of the time. It should be noted that these data are derived from surveys. The Probability of Saving: Being another survey derived data, expectation of possible future savings may also be correlated since these savings are useful for funding new businesses. Unemployment: High unemployment rate means that there are more potential entrepreneurs and employees for new firms. Since it is hard for anyone to take the risk of abandoning already established living standards by resigning, already unemployed people are more likely to start new businesses.

b.Data Visualisation and Analysis

Target Variable Analysis and Trend Component

Firstly, it would be a good idea to analyze our main data, the number of newly establish firms, to see any pattern which may be useful in the linear model. So we start by visualizing the data in a plot:

It can be easily seen that there is an uptrend in data except the 2020 April-May which is probably because of the uncertainty due to emergence of pandemic. So a trend component should be added to linear model. Also the highs and lows in years generally coincide with same months: highs on January, lows between August-November. The first model with the trend component and yearly seasonality component can be seen below after needed manipulations:

By checking p-values of F and T statistics, we can easily say that trend and months are significant factors. However, there is still a large unexplained portion of variance as R-squared value is 0.6368. We will try to explain them using the independent variables. But first, lets check the residuals of the model to see if assumptions of linear models hold or not:

## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 16
## 
## data:  Residuals
## LM test = 39.584, df = 16, p-value = 0.0008951

Zero mean for residuals assumption seems to be satisfied. Unchanging variance assumption is not explicitly violated except the pandemic uncertainty period. Residuals are highly autocorrelated at lag 1 although we used trend component. In order to get rid of autocorrelation, we can use lagged residual values as a parameter in linear model:

Unemployment rate also does not seem to have any correlation with residuals.

3.Conclusion

Although we didnt incorporate the variables to our linear model except industrial production, they may still be related to target variable. Trend and yearly seasonality components might be the reason why they seem useless to our model since they include the effect of economic parameters with similar patterns. To sum up, we were able to explain the behavior of newly established firms data with the dummy variables created for trend and yearly patterns. The only independent data we used in our model was industrial production volume data. The final version of our model is as follows:
